{{short description|Solar barge of the sun god Ra in Ancient Egyptian mythology}}
{{Infobox deity | type = Egyptian | name = Atet | image = Ra Barque.jpg | caption = The solar boat Atet | deity_of = The boat of the sun | cult_center = | symbol = boat | parents = | siblings = | consort = | offspring = }}
The '''Atet''' ({{lang-egy|[[wikt:ꜥḏt|ꜥḏt]]}}) was the [[Solar deity#Solar barge and sun chariot|solar barge]] of the [[Solar deity|sun god]] [[Ra]] in the [[Egyptian mythology|mythology]] of the [[ancient Egypt]]ians. It was also known as the '''Mandjet''' ({{lang-egy|[[wikt:mꜥnḏt|mꜥnḏt]]}}), the '''Boat of Millions of Years''' ({{lang-egy|[[wikt:wjꜣ-n-ḥḥw|wjꜣ-n-ḥḥw]]}}), and, during the night, as the '''Mesektet''' ({{lang-egy|[[wikt:msktt|msktt]]}}).
Ra&nbsp;— variously conflated with other solar gods such as [[Amun]] and [[Hathor]]&nbsp;— was said to travel through the sky on the barge, providing light to the world.<ref>{{citation |contribution-url=http://www.touregypt.net/godsofegypt/sunboat.htm |contribution=The Sun Boat |title=The Gods of Ancient Egypt |publisher=Tour Egypt |accessdate=7 March 2017 }}.</ref> Each twelfth of his journey formed one of the twelve [[Egyptian hours]] of the day, each overseen by a protective deity. Ra then rode the Atet through the [[Egyptian underworld|underworld]], with each hour of the night considered a gate overseen by twelve more protective deities. Passing through all of these while fending off various destructive monsters, Ra reappeared each day on the eastern horizon.
The progress of Ra upon the Atet was sometimes conceived as his daily growth, decline, death, and resurrection and it appears in the symbology of Egyptian mortuary texts.
== In other media ==
Ra's ship appears in the 2016 film [[Gods of Egypt (film)|Gods of Egypt]]. In the film, the ship appears as a seafaring ship that drags the Sun across the sky.
